+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JmKXNX5swAZALKU8SvhojV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017MajuuWD6p8jdmQcaxATn2","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"node -e \"\n// Verify the lex ordering logic for sets.\n// The spec says: sorted button indices, lex smallest.\n// [0,2] vs [1,3]: Compare first elements: 0 < 1, so [0,2] is lex smaller.\n// [0,3] vs [0,2]: Compare second elements: 3 > 2, so [0,2] is lex smaller.\n// [0,1] vs [0,2]: second element 1 < 2, so [0,1] is smaller.\n//\n// In the bigint representation:\n// [0,2] = bit 0 and bit 2 set = 0b101 = 5\n// [1,3] = bit 1 and bit 3 set = 0b1010 = 10\n// diff = 5 ^ 10 = 15 = 0b1111, lowestDiff = 1 (bit 0)\n// 5 & 1 = 1 (truthy) => 5 is lex smaller => [0,2] is lex smaller. CORRECT.\n//\n// [0,3] = 0b1001 = 9\n// [0,2] = 0b0101 = 5\n// diff = 9 ^ 5 = 12 = 0b1100, lowestDiff = 4 (bit 2)\n// isLexSmaller(5, 9): 5 & 4 = 4 (truthy) => 5 is lex smaller => [0,2] < [0,3]. CORRECT.\n//\n// But wait, what about different-size sets with same weight?\n// Same weight is already guaranteed by the w === bestWeight check. Good.\n//\n// Actually, re-read the lex comparison more carefully.\n// Sets of same size: [0,2] vs [1,3]\n// As sorted arrays: [0,2] < [1,3] because 0 < 1.\n// In bigint: bit 0 is the first difference, currentSol has it => currentSol is lex smaller. Correct.\n//\n// [1,2] = 0b110 = 6 vs [0,3] = 0b1001 = 9\n// diff = 6 ^ 9 = 15, lowestDiff = 1 (bit 0)\n// isLexSmaller(6, 9): 6 & 1 = 0 => false. So 9 ([0,3]) is lex smaller.\n// As arrays: [0,3] vs [1,2]. First element: 0 < 1 => [0,3] is smaller. CORRECT.\nconsole.log('Lex ordering logic verification passed');\n\n// Now check: for different-SIZE sets with same popcount -- this can't happen since\n// popcount IS the size. So same weight = same size. Good.\n\"\n","description":"Verify lex ordering logic for toggle sets"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"us