+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_017A7A6aEaihH7B7ao3V2Gya","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KDotnJYfg3MsxTXCtZb8X9","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"node -e \"\n// Check the performance of counter enumeration.\n// With 5M enumeration limit and numFree free variables:\n// Each iteration calls computeSolution which is O(numFree * m) for the free var part\n// and O(rank * m) for the pivot var part. Total per iteration: O(m^2) since rank+numFree=m.\n// With m=40: O(1600) per iteration.\n// 5M iterations * 1600 ops = 8 billion ops. This might be too slow for 5 seconds.\n//\n// Let's be more precise: computeSolution loops rank times, each doing m iterations.\n// rank <= 40, m <= 40. So each computeSolution call does up to 40*40 = 1600 ops.\n// 5M * 1600 = 8 billion. At ~100M simple ops/sec in JS: ~80 seconds. Too slow!\n//\n// But wait, for the enumeration to have 5M iterations, we need modulus^numFree <= 5M.\n// With modulus=2, numFree=22: 2^22 = 4.2M. computeSolution: O(22 * 40 + 40) -- \n// but actually the loop does ALL m columns, not just free.\n// So it's really O(rank * m) = O(40 * 40) = 1600 per call.\n// 4.2M * 1600 = 6.7 billion. This is likely too slow.\n//\n// Actually, let me reconsider: m and rank are at most 40 in the worst case,\n// but if modulus=2 and numFree=22, then rank = m - 22 = 18 (if m=40).\n// computeSolution: numFree assignments (22 ops) + rank iterations (18 * 40 = 720 ops).\n// Total per iteration: ~740 ops. 4.2M * 740 = ~3.1 billion. Still borderline.\nconsole.log('5M enumeration limit might be too aggressive for complex cases');\nconsole.log('But typical cases with small modulus and few free vars should be fast');\n\"\n","description":"Analyze counter enumeration performance at scale"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":470,"cache_read_input_tokens":45992,"cache_creation"